Small LCDM cosmological simulation generated by C. Power. Cosmology
is WMAP9 and the box is 100Mpc/h in size with 64^3 particles.
We use a softening length of 1/25th of the mean inter-particle separation.

The ICs have been generated to run with Gadget-2 so we need to switch
on the options to cancel the h-factors and a-factors at reading time.

This example runs SWIFT in dark-matter-only mode with inline FOF group
finding enabled. The resulting snapshots are then analysed with HBT-HERONS
to produce subhalo catalogues and merger trees.

MD5 checksum of the ICs:
08736c3101fd738e22f5159f78e6022b  small_cosmo_volume.hdf5

### Compiling SWIFT

SWIFT requires FOF support to be enabled at configure time (./configure --enable-fof)

### Compiling HBT-HERONS

Full installation instructions are at https://hbt-herons.strw.leidenuniv.nl/installation/.
Since this is a dark-matter-only simulation, compile with the HBT_DM_ONLY flag:

    mkdir build && cd build
    cmake ../ -DHBT_DM_ONLY=On && make -j 4

### How to run

Before running, set hbt_path, num_mpi_ranks, and num_omp_threads at the top of run.sh to
point to your HBT-HERONS build and the desired number of processes. Then:

    ./run.sh

This will:
1. Download the initial conditions (if not already present).
2. Run SWIFT with self-gravity and inline FOF, writing 59 snapshots from z=9 to
   z=0 into ./outputs/SWIFT/. Note we require a large number of snapshots to
   produce reliable results as HBT-HERONS is a history-based subhalo finder.
3. Run HBT-HERONS to produce subhalo catalogues in ./outputs/HBT-HERONS/.
4. Plot the z=0 halo mass function and save it as HMF.png.

### Plotting script

plotHMF.py shows a minimal example of loading HBT-HERONS catalogues using
HBTReader (HBT-HERONS/toolbox/HBTReader.py). More detailed example scripts
covering merger trees, satellite populations and population-level statistics
can be found at https://hbt-herons.strw.leidenuniv.nl/examples/overview/
